<subSubSection id="65226B0E1502167AE1799FBEA9D2ED54" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" type="description">
<paragraph id="87CA934CE641FDF43E7CAD2032C17A97" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5CB2929C9832FDE2FBCA431CA4F61222" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">
<emphasis id="3D351F7ACF34FB665A3F60E8947DD7D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Saprobic</emphasis>
on culms of bamboo. 
<emphasis id="67A3289448A5DDEDC994542369FA835D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Sexual morph</emphasis>
: Undetermined. 
<emphasis id="3B97EED15F486EBFF3233C90E7942DE2" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Asexual morph</emphasis>
: Hyphomycetous (Figs 
<figureCitation id="02358F7ADB680E3C8882F1317F291978" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F5723720" captionText="Figure 1. Distoseptispora bambusae (MFLU 20 - 0261, holotype, collected from China) a, b. Colonies on natural substrate; c, d. Conidiophore with Conidia; e. Conidiophore; f. Conidiogenous cell; g - j. Conidia; k. Germinating conidium; l, m. Colony on PDA. Scale bars: c-e, k = 20 μm, f-j = 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e53678.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/399702" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="1C7A0522D491F1C5D9D4C69A922713AB" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F5723724" captionText="Figure 2. Distoseptispora bambusae (MFLU 17 - 1653, paratype, collected from Thailand). a, b. Colonies on natural substrate; c - g. Conidia attached to conidiophores; h - k. Conidia; l. Germinating conidium. Scale Bars: c = 50 μm, d-l = 25 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e53678.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/399703" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">2</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="BF330A4B99D93B9A18EC1E9696C05670" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Colonies</emphasis>
effuse, brown to dark-brown, hairy. 
<emphasis id="193DF4F76D156429F78ED960295B151F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Mycelium</emphasis>
mostly immersed, composed of pale to dark brown, septate, branched, smooth, hyaline to subhyaline hyphae. 
<emphasis id="DE1596995C731A8E0074B91444703564" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Conidiophores</emphasis>
macronematous, mononematous, septate, single or in groups of 2 or 3, erect, cylindrical, straight or slightly flexuous, olivaceous or brown, robust at the base 40-96 
<normalizedToken id="DC9325B5A007588BD0E73D12AC9B4DBA" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-5.5 
<normalizedToken id="7F85CF01D3D0B861919EB4EC9B3C1D4F" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(x̅ = 69 
<normalizedToken id="D955881A1C8B1DBF37A8A21471543D90" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5 
<normalizedToken id="207C7982BC2C1D05136AFF02133086D4" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, n = 10). 
<emphasis id="B3EA6812AD53F84FA3F6881D34390E2F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Conidiogenous cells</emphasis>
blastic, integrated, terminal, cylindrical, olivaceous or brown 9-19 
<normalizedToken id="589E5B2E47738CDCF2A4EBAE28B347B3" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-5 
<normalizedToken id="753E053F0C978E73D7BFC417D7E42E13" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(x̅ = 15 
<normalizedToken id="43F4C74CCD993935C321CF2CEF220C69" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4.5 
<normalizedToken id="C56AD608A9198DF42F58DEFFFC6D1D41" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, n = 15). 
<emphasis id="F1B7CDB31A58228F725E5BB35EDA6926" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Conidia</emphasis>
acrogenous, solitary, straight, obclavate, septate, thick-walled, rounded at the apex, truncate at the base, tapering towards apex, olivaceous or brown, 45-74 
<normalizedToken id="899FA324DB9F13CE623CC346526EC97B" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
long (x̅ = 60.5 
<normalizedToken id="F920BFA37AB9C74C1E5CBF85A7295FDE" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, n = 20), 5.5-9.5 
<normalizedToken id="3235FD1F6A67D27A915E4E6ECB779EDC" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
at the widest (x̅ = 7.5 
<normalizedToken id="463FDE9694ADDB0695185C45F5CB6BB0" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, n = 20).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6F0F0B729E073936674F9BC2A4FF6D21" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Culture characteristics: Conidia germinated on PDA within 12 hours and germ tubes were produced from both ends. Colony reached 30 mm in 4 weeks at 26℃ on PDA media, circular, flat, surface rough, grey from above, brown from below, edge entire.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E4A695C8A281C2E17AD491CBF1FB8A9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" type="notes">
<paragraph id="81BDC7E036149A83E5F620838DEDFD53" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">
<emphasis id="E801AC1753B5C212A9EAEE5BE78CF824" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B4886FF765B263B0F23BBD2DD67A1B57" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">
The morphological characteristics of 
<taxonomicName id="D4AE4CBC77C507630190CD46F606737C" authorityName="Y. R. Sun, I. D. Goonasekara, Yong Wang bis &amp; K. D. Hyde" authorityYear="2020" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Distoseptisporaceae" genus="Distoseptispora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Distoseptispora bambusae" order="Distoseptisporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="bambusae">
<emphasis id="19EA511CE81FB91BDB84E1A5CA5A66A4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Distoseptispora bambusae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
match well with the generic concept of 
<taxonomicName id="9E780160BFBD49BBCD0A355D557399E0" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Distoseptisporaceae" genus="Distoseptispora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Distoseptispora" order="Distoseptisporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B6C9589FA4037B01D1EEDD1460ED57CD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Distoseptispora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7EF7CB9E57CBB56BB4C191985423E787" author="Su, Hong Yan" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" pagination="375 - 409" refId="B5724128" refString="Su, Hong Yan, Hyde, Kevin D, Maharachchikumbura, Sajeewa S N, Ariyawansa, Hiran A, Luo, Zong Long, Promputtha, Itthayakorn, Tian, Qing, Lin, Chuan Gen, Shang, Qiu Ju, Zhao, Yong Chang, Chai, Hong Mei, Liu, Xiao Ying, Bahkali, Ali H, Bhat, Jayarama D, McKenzie, Eric H C, Zhou, De Qun, 2016. The families Distoseptisporaceae fam. nov., Kirschsteiniotheliaceae, Sporormiaceae and Torulaceae, with new species from freshwater in Yunnan Province, China. Fungal Diversity 80: 375 - 409" title="The families Distoseptisporaceae fam. nov., Kirschsteiniotheliaceae, Sporormiaceae and Torulaceae, with new species from freshwater in Yunnan Province, China" volume="80" year="2016">Su et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
). Multi-gene analyses showed that 
<taxonomicName id="734EBF063ED735374CE1B678A248FE76" genus="D." lsidName="D. bambusae" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" rank="species" species="bambusae">D. bambusae</taxonomicName>
is a phylogenetically-distinct species, most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="B96FE02BD243DCE2ACAD25E56610856B" genus="D." lsidName="D. suoluoensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" rank="species" species="suoluoensis">D. suoluoensis</taxonomicName>
, a species isolated from submerged wood in a freshwater habitat (
<bibRefCitation id="C2FFD93E007A93D5BC52E32D2E07833C" author="Yang, Jing" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Progress" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" pagination="591 - 616" refId="B5724213" refString="Yang, Jing, Maharachchikumbura, Sajeewa S N, Liu, Jian Kui, Hyde, Kevin D, Jones, E B Gareth, Al-Sadi, Abdullah M, Liu, Zuo Yi, 2018. Pseudostanjehughesia aquitropica gen. et sp. nov. and Sporidesmium sensu lato species from freshwater habitats. Mycological Progress 17: 591 - 616" title="Pseudostanjehughesia aquitropica gen. et sp. nov. and Sporidesmium sensu lato species from freshwater habitats" volume="17" year="2018">Yang et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="67740FC5EB722096B2999847B33B3D95" authorityName="Y. R. Sun, I. D. Goonasekara, Yong Wang bis &amp; K. D. Hyde" authorityYear="2020" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Distoseptisporaceae" genus="Distoseptispora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Distoseptispora bambusae" order="Distoseptisporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="bambusae">
<emphasis id="A784957E879E0EB8B49C0DF86AA1721B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">Distoseptispora bambusae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has shorter conidiophores (40-96 vs. 80-250 
<normalizedToken id="30BB0DCFDA4391957A8CCA693DCE9437" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) and shorter conidia (45-74 vs. (65-) 80-125(-145) 
<normalizedToken id="D6AB76744AC393E49F1A7E3E31D50322" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) than those of 
<taxonomicName id="2CDAA71262694E7B3090178B3BC9E904" genus="D." lsidName="D. suoluoensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" rank="species" species="suoluoensis">
<emphasis id="921B12FA608FF2E639A88815BF98325D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">D. suoluoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="F6189FB1373A69B699C98A2DA5C1DDE1" author="Yang, Jing" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Progress" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" pagination="591 - 616" refId="B5724213" refString="Yang, Jing, Maharachchikumbura, Sajeewa S N, Liu, Jian Kui, Hyde, Kevin D, Jones, E B Gareth, Al-Sadi, Abdullah M, Liu, Zuo Yi, 2018. Pseudostanjehughesia aquitropica gen. et sp. nov. and Sporidesmium sensu lato species from freshwater habitats. Mycological Progress 17: 591 - 616" title="Pseudostanjehughesia aquitropica gen. et sp. nov. and Sporidesmium sensu lato species from freshwater habitats" volume="17" year="2018">Yang et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Our two specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="55F3D5FFCAC43BF003AFD01B03F14AFF" genus="D." lsidName="D. bambusae" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" rank="species" species="bambusae">
<emphasis id="C4E4AB92294153317426791BDCDF2129" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678">D. bambusae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were similar in morphology, but polyblastic conidiogenous cells were observed from the Chinese specimen, while the Thai specimen has only monoblastic conidiogenous cells. These may be due to geographical differences and the different observation period. Although the two strains clustered together with short branches in the phylogenetic tree, comparisons of ITS sequences showed that there are 3 bp (base pair) differences without gaps between two strains and we identified them as the same species following the guidelines for species delineation proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="CBA8D4B1303CADDA71D9455B565A6C6B" author="Jeewon, R" journalOrPublisher="Mycosphere" pageId="0" pageNumber="53678" pagination="1669 - 1677" refId="B5724118" refString="Jeewon, R, Hyde, K D, 2016. Establishing species boundaries and new taxa among fungi: recommendations to resolve taxonomic ambiguities. Mycosphere 7 (11): 1669 - 1677" title="Establishing species boundaries and new taxa among fungi: recommendations to resolve taxonomic ambiguities" volume="7" year="2016">Jeewon and Hyde (2016)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
